Dissertation Project: Modelling Universal Basic Income for an AI-Disrupted Labour Market¶

This notebook is the reproducible workflow accompanying the dissertation. It is organised to mirror the thesis:

  1. Environment Setup – imports, Drive mount, file paths, helpers.
  2. Data Loading & Validation – import raw SPSS datasets (+ metadata), quality checks.
  3. Feature Engineering – derive key household & demographic features.
  4. Simulation – disposable income under policy scenarios.
  5. Machine Learning – predictive models on financial vulnerability outcomes.

All intermediate outputs (tables, figures, processed datasets) are saved under DATA_DIR for reproducibility.

1 Environment Setup¶

Prepare the working environment for the dissertation analysis.

  • Library Imports
    Load core packages for data analysis (numpy, pandas), visualisation (matplotlib, seaborn), file handling, and machine learning (scikit-learn).

  • Reproducibility
    Set a fixed random seed so any stochastic steps (e.g., train/test split) are repeatable.

  • Directory Paths
    Define paths for the project’s data and for outputs (figures/, tables/, snapshots/) so results are saved in a consistent, reproducible structure.

  • Helper Functions
    Include small utilities (e.g., a file checker) to fail fast with clear messages if required inputs are missing.

CONFIG["FIG_DIR"].mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

# Helper: assert a file exists
def check_file(path: Path):
    """Raise error if file not found, otherwise confirm."""
    if not path.exists():
        raise FileNotFoundError(f"❌ File not found: {path}")
    print(f"✅ {path} found")

# Consistent plot style
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")         # background + grid
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (8, 5)  # default figure size

# ---- Visualisation helpers (use CONFIG) ----
def safe_hist(series: pd.Series, title: str, outfile: str):
    """Histogram + KDE for a numeric series; silently skips if no numeric data."""
    s = pd.to_numeric(series, errors="coerce").dropna()
    if s.empty:
        print(f"[skip] {series.name}: no numeric data")
        return
    plt.figure()
    sns.histplot(s, bins=30, kde=True, color="steelblue")
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(series.name)
    plt.ylabel("Frequency")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(CONFIG["FIG_DIR"] / outfile, dpi=CONFIG["FIG_DPI"], bbox_inches="tight")
    plt.show()

2 Data Loading & Validation¶

Load the raw LCFS datasets (household and person files), performs validation checks, and saves defensive snapshots for reproducibility.

Specifically, it:

  • Defines file paths for raw .sav files and creates organised output folders.
  • Loads raw household (DV_HH) and person-level (DVPER) datasets.
  • Saves compressed snapshots (.pkl.gz) to Google Drive for faster reloads in future runs.
  • Performs data quality checks:
    • Shapes and dimensions of datasets.
    • Duplicate detection.
    • Missingness rates for key variables.
    • Numeric and categorical summaries.
  • Produces diagnostic visuals (bar plots, histograms, correlation heatmaps) and saves them to the figures folder for inclusion in the appendix.

This ensures all downstream steps (feature engineering, simulations, ML) operate on a validated, well-documented dataset.

# 2.2 Load datasets

# Full paths (for clarity)
hh_path    = HH_FILE
per_path   = PER_FILE
house_path = HOUSE_FILE
rawper_path = RAWPER_FILE

# Snapshot file paths
hh_snap    = SNAP_DIR / "hh_raw.pkl.gz"
per_snap   = SNAP_DIR / "per_raw.pkl.gz"
house_snap = SNAP_DIR / "house_raw.pkl.gz"
rawper_snap = SNAP_DIR/ "rawper_raw.pkl.gz"

# Try to load from snapshots if all exist
if hh_snap.exists() and per_snap.exists() and house_snap.exists() and rawper_snap.exists():
    hh_df    = pd.read_pickle(hh_snap)
    per_df   = pd.read_pickle(per_snap)
    house_df = pd.read_pickle(house_snap)
    rawper_df = pd.read_pickle(rawper_snap)
    print("✅ Loaded household, person & house datasets from snapshots")
else:
    # Otherwise, read raw .sav with metadata (kept here if needed later)
    hh_df,    hh_meta    = pyreadstat.read_sav(str(hh_path))
    per_df,   per_meta   = pyreadstat.read_sav(str(per_path))
    house_df, house_meta = pyreadstat.read_sav(str(house_path))
    rawper_df, rawper_meta = pyreadstat.read_sav(str(rawper_path))

    # Save pristine copies as compressed snapshots
    hh_df.to_pickle(hh_snap, compression="gzip")
    per_df.to_pickle(per_snap, compression="gzip")
    house_df.to_pickle(house_snap, compression="gzip")
    rawper_df.to_pickle(rawper_snap, compression="gzip")
    print("Saved raw snapshots:", hh_snap.name, per_snap.name, house_snap.name, rawper_snap.name)

# Defensive copies so raw stays intact (optional but handy)
hh_raw    = hh_df.copy()
per_raw   = per_df.copy()
house_raw = house_df.copy()
rawper_raw = rawper_df.copy()

# 2.4 Validation & Auto-detect key variables (works with hh_df, per_df, house_df, rawper_df)

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from pathlib import Path

# ---------- helpers ----------
def pick_col(df, candidates):
    """Return the first candidate that exists in df.columns (case-insensitive safe)."""
    if df is None:
        return None
    cols_lower = {c.lower(): c for c in df.columns}
    for c in candidates:
        if c is None:
            continue
        if c.lower() in cols_lower:
            return cols_lower[c.lower()]
    return None

def save_value_counts(df, col, out_path, top=30):
    try:
        vc = df[col].value_counts(dropna=False).head(top)
        vc.to_frame("count").to_csv(out_path)
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"[warn] could not save value counts for {col}: {e}")

# ---------- candidate lists (robust to naming variants) ----------
# Keys
CASE_CAND_HH   = ["case", "Case", "CASE", "Case Number", "CASEID", "CaseID"]
CASE_CAND_PER  = CASE_CAND_HH
PERSON_CAND    = ["Person", "PERSON", "person", "PERSNO", "Person number"]

def add_dup(df, name, subset):
    if df is None or any(c is None for c in subset):
        dup_rows.append({"dataset": name, "key": str(subset), "dup_rows": "n/a"})
        return
    n_dups = int(df.duplicated(subset=subset).sum())
    dup_rows.append({"dataset": name, "key": str(subset), "dup_rows": n_dups})

# One-column case keys
add_dup(hh_df,     "RAW_HH",        [CASE_COL_HH])
add_dup(house_df,  "LCFS_HOUSE",    [CASE_COL_HOUSE])

# Two-column (case, person) keys
add_dup(per_df,    "DVPER",         [CASE_COL_PER, PERSON_COL])
add_dup(rawper_df, "RAW_PER",       [CASE_COL_RAWPER, RPER_PERSON_COL])

import numpy as np

FIG_DPI = CONFIG.get("FIG_DPI", 150)

# ----------------- helpers -----------------
def bar_counts(series, title, outfile, topn=None):
    if series is None:
        print(f"[skip] {title}: no series")
        return
    vc = series.value_counts(dropna=False)
    if topn is not None:
        vc = vc.head(topn)
    plt.figure()
    vc.sort_values(ascending=False).plot(kind="bar")
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(series.name)
    plt.ylabel("count")
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(FIG_DIR / outfile, dpi=FIG_DPI, bbox_inches="tight")
    plt.show()

def corr_heatmap(df_subset, title, outfile):
    # numeric-only, drop rows with any NA across chosen columns
    num = df_subset.select_dtypes(include=np.number).dropna()
    if num.shape[1] < 2 or num.shape[0] < 2:
        print("[skip] not enough numeric data for correlation heatmap")
        return
    C = num.corr(method="pearson")
    plt.figure()
    sns.heatmap(C, annot=False, cmap="vlag", center=0)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(FIG_DIR / outfile, dpi=FIG_DPI, bbox_inches="tight")
    plt.show()

def missing_bar(df, title, outfile):
    s = df.isna().mean().sort_values(ascending=False).head(20).rename("na_rate")
    plt.figure()
    s.plot(kind="barh")
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel("na_rate")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(FIG_DIR / outfile, dpi=FIG_DPI, bbox_inches="tight")
    plt.show()

def missing_heatmap(df, title, outfile, n_rows=200, n_cols=30):
    # purely illustrative: small patch of the data to show 'patchiness'
    if df.shape[1] == 0:
        print("[skip] empty df for missing heatmap")
        return
    cols = df.isna().mean().sort_values(ascending=False).head(n_cols).index
    if len(cols) == 0:
        print("[skip] no missingness to plot")
        return
    n = min(n_rows, len(df))
    samp = df.sample(n=n, random_state=42)
    plt.figure()
    sns.heatmap(samp[cols].isna(), cbar=False)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(FIG_DIR / outfile, dpi=FIG_DPI, bbox_inches="tight")
    plt.show()

def pick_first(df, candidates):
    if df is None:
        return None
    for c in candidates:
        if c in df.columns:
            return c
        # case-insensitive tolerance
        for col in df.columns:
            if str(col).lower() == str(c).lower():
                return col
    return None

3 Feature Engineering¶

Clean variables, merge the three sources (RAW_HH, DVPER, LCFS), and build a single tidy dataset for analysis & modelling.

  • Select & rename canonical columns
    • Keys: case, Person (where relevant), HRP flag (A003==1), survey year/quarter.
    • Household composition: DVHsize, NumAdult, NumChild, etc.
    • Income: prefer LCFS weekly disposable household income (P389p); keep any alternates for checks.
    • Region / tenure / weights if available (e.g., Mscale, OECDSc, survey weights).
  • Filter to one household row
    • Keep one person per household (HRP) from DVPER and join to RAW_HH/LCFS by case.
  • Create derived variables
    • Equivalised household size (e.g., OECD scale), equivalised disposable income.
    • Age bands (if age present), dependency ratios, child/adult flags.
    • Binary targets you’ll need later (e.g., below 60% median income baseline).
  • Handle missingness
    • Decide rules: drop rows with missing key fields vs. simple imputations (median for numeric; “Unknown” for categorical).
    • Document the rule you apply.
  • Make codes human-readable
    • Map Sex, Employment status (FES/ES2000) to labels.
    • Keep a small dict/table of code → label in /tables/section3/.
  • Outliers & scaling (optional)
    • Winsorise extreme incomes, or keep a raw vs. trimmed column.
    • Create log_income for models that like symmetry.

# 3.0 Build tidy merge (one row per household)

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from pathlib import Path

FIG3 = Path(CONFIG["FIG_DIR"]) / "section3"
TAB3 = Path(CONFIG["DATA_DIR"]) / "tables" / "section3"
OUT3 = Path(CONFIG["DATA_DIR"]) / "snapshots"
for d in (FIG3, TAB3, OUT3):
    d.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

vp = VARIABLE_PLAN  # <-- from Section 2.4

# ---------- A) Pre-merge checks ----------
def assert_unique(df, cols, name):
    if df is None or any(c is None for c in cols):
        print(f"[note] skip uniqueness check for {name}")
        return
    dups = df.duplicated(subset=[c for c in cols if c in df.columns]).sum()
    print(f"[check] duplicates on {name} ->", dups)

# standardise key dtypes early (helps the joins)
def coerce_keys(df, case_col, person_col=None):
    if df is None: return
    if case_col and case_col in df.columns:
        df[case_col] = pd.to_numeric(df[case_col], errors="coerce").astype("Int64")
    if person_col and person_col in df.columns:
        df[person_col] = pd.to_numeric(df[person_col], errors="coerce").astype("Int64")

CASE_HH   = vp["keys"]["case"]
PERSON_COL= vp["keys"]["person"]

coerce_keys(hh_df,     CASE_HH, None)
coerce_keys(house_df,  CASE_HH, None)
coerce_keys(per_df,    CASE_HH, PERSON_COL)
coerce_keys(rawper_df, CASE_HH, PERSON_COL)

assert_unique(hh_df,     [CASE_HH],                      "hh_df:case")
assert_unique(house_df,  [CASE_HH],                      "house_df:case")
assert_unique(per_df,    [CASE_HH, PERSON_COL],          "per_df:(case,person)")
if 'rawper_df' in globals():
    assert_unique(rawper_df, [CASE_HH, PERSON_COL],      "rawper_df:(case,person)")

# ---------- B) Build one-person row (HRP) ----------
HRP_FLAG = vp["hrp"]["flag"]
AGE_COL  = vp["hrp"]["age"]

if HRP_FLAG and HRP_FLAG in per_df.columns:
    hrp = per_df.loc[per_df[HRP_FLAG] == 1].copy()
    # if >1 HRP flagged in a case, keep the oldest
    if AGE_COL and AGE_COL in hrp.columns:
        hrp[AGE_COL] = pd.to_numeric(hrp[AGE_COL], errors="coerce")
        hrp = hrp.sort_values([CASE_HH, AGE_COL], ascending=[True, False]).drop_duplicates(CASE_HH)
    else:
        hrp = hrp.drop_duplicates(CASE_HH)
else:
    # fallback: pick oldest person in each household
    print("[note] No HRP flag found; using oldest person per household as HRP.")
    tmp = per_df.copy()
    if AGE_COL and AGE_COL in tmp.columns:
        tmp[AGE_COL] = pd.to_numeric(tmp[AGE_COL], errors="coerce")
        hrp = tmp.sort_values([CASE_HH, AGE_COL], ascending=[True, False]).drop_duplicates(CASE_HH)
    else:
        hrp = tmp.drop_duplicates(CASE_HH)

# Keep columns we’ll need later (IMPORTANT: keep PERSON_COL so we can fetch education)
keep_cols = [c for c in [
    CASE_HH, PERSON_COL, AGE_COL,
    vp["demo"].get("sex"), vp["demo"].get("emp"),
    vp["demo"].get("mar"), vp["demo"].get("eth")
] if c and c in per_df.columns]
hrp = hrp[keep_cols].copy()

# ---------- C) Pull HRP education (prefer per_df, else rawper_df) ----------
educ_col = vp["demo"].get("educ")
hrp["educ_code"] = pd.NA  # create destination

# (1) from per_df if present
if educ_col and educ_col in per_df.columns:
    # merge on (case, person) to pull that person’s education
    hrp = hrp.merge(
        per_df[[CASE_HH, PERSON_COL, educ_col]],
        on=[CASE_HH, PERSON_COL],
        how="left",
        suffixes=("", "_pereduc")
    )
    # write into educ_code
    if educ_col in hrp.columns:
        hrp["educ_code"] = hrp[educ_col]
        hrp.drop(columns=[educ_col], inplace=True, errors="ignore")

# (2) else try rawper_df if available
if hrp["educ_code"].isna().all() and 'rawper_df' in globals() and rawper_df is not None:
    if educ_col and educ_col in rawper_df.columns and PERSON_COL in hrp.columns:
        hrp = hrp.merge(
            rawper_df[[CASE_HH, PERSON_COL, educ_col]],
            on=[CASE_HH, PERSON_COL],
            how="left",
            suffixes=("", "_raweduc")
        )
        if educ_col in hrp.columns:
            hrp["educ_code"] = hrp["educ_code"].fillna(hrp[educ_col])
            hrp.drop(columns=[educ_col], inplace=True, errors="ignore")
    else:
        print("[note] Could not detect education in rawper_df (or no person key).")

# we no longer need PERSON_COL in the final household row
if PERSON_COL in hrp.columns:
    hrp.drop(columns=[PERSON_COL], inplace=True)

# ---------- D) Select household & LCFS columns ----------
HH_COLS = [c for c in [CASE_HH, vp["comp"].get("hhsize"), vp["comp"].get("n_adult"), vp["comp"].get("n_child")] if c and c in hh_df.columns]
hh_keep = hh_df[HH_COLS].copy()

HOUSE_COLS = [c for c in [
    CASE_HH, vp["income"].get("weekly_disp_hh"),
    vp["demo"].get("eq_scale"), vp["demo"].get("region"),
    vp["demo"].get("tenure")
] if c and c in house_df.columns]
house_keep = house_df[HOUSE_COLS].copy()

# Optional: lone-parent from rawper_df
lp_keep = None
lone_col = vp["demo"].get("lone_parent")
if 'rawper_df' in globals() and rawper_df is not None and lone_col and lone_col in rawper_df.columns:
    lp_keep = rawper_df[[CASE_HH, lone_col]].drop_duplicates(CASE_HH)

# ---------- E) Merge: HH + HRP -> + LCFS -> + rawper optional ----------
merged = hh_keep.merge(hrp, on=CASE_HH, how="left", suffixes=("", "_hrp"))
merged = merged.merge(house_keep, on=CASE_HH, how="left")
if lp_keep is not None:
    merged = merged.merge(lp_keep, on=CASE_HH, how="left")

print("Shapes:",
      "\n hh_keep ", hh_keep.shape,
      "\n hrp     ", hrp.shape,
      "\n house   ", house_keep.shape,
      "\n rawper  ", lp_keep.shape if lp_keep is not None else None,
      "\n -> merged", merged.shape)

# ---------- F) Clear names ----------
rename_map = {}
rename_map[vp["comp"].get("hhsize")]  = "hh_size"
rename_map[vp["comp"].get("n_adult")] = "n_adult"
rename_map[vp["comp"].get("n_child")] = "n_child"
if AGE_COL and AGE_COL in merged.columns:              rename_map[AGE_COL]                 = "age"
if vp["demo"].get("sex")  in merged.columns:           rename_map[vp["demo"]["sex"]]       = "sex_code"
if vp["demo"].get("emp")  in merged.columns:           rename_map[vp["demo"]["emp"]]       = "emp_code"
if vp["demo"].get("eth")  in merged.columns:           rename_map[vp["demo"]["eth"]]       = "eth_code"
if vp["demo"].get("mar")  in merged.columns:           rename_map[vp["demo"]["mar"]]       = "mar_code"
if vp["demo"].get("region") in merged.columns:         rename_map[vp["demo"]["region"]]    = "region_code"
if vp["demo"].get("tenure") in merged.columns:         rename_map[vp["demo"]["tenure"]]    = "tenure_code"
if vp["income"].get("weekly_disp_hh") in merged.columns:
    rename_map[vp["income"]["weekly_disp_hh"]] = "disp_income_week"
if vp["demo"].get("eq_scale") in merged.columns:       rename_map[vp["demo"]["eq_scale"]]  = "eq_scale"
if lone_col and lone_col in merged.columns:            rename_map[lone_col]                = "lone_parent"

merged = merged.rename(columns=rename_map)

# quick diagnostics
key_fields = [c for c in ["hh_size", "n_adult", "n_child", "disp_income_week"] if c in merged.columns]
print("Missing rate on key fields:")
print(merged[key_fields].isna().mean().sort_values(ascending=False))

                            "region_code","tenure_code","lone_parent","educ_code",
                            "disp_income_week","eq_scale") if c in merged.columns]

merged[preview_cols].to_csv(TAB3 / "feature_merge_head.csv", index=False)

# --- Standardise final column names (run AFTER creating `merged`) ---

def standardise_columns(df, VP):
    rename_map = {}

    # keys
    if VP["keys"].get("case") in df.columns:
        rename_map[VP["keys"]["case"]] = "case"
    if VP["hrp"].get("age") in df.columns:
        rename_map[VP["hrp"]["age"]] = "age"

    # composition
    comp = VP.get("comp", {})
    if comp.get("hhsize") in df.columns:
        rename_map[comp["hhsize"]] = "hh_size"
    if comp.get("n_adult") in df.columns:
        rename_map[comp["n_adult"]] = "n_adult"
    if comp.get("n_child") in df.columns:
        rename_map[comp["n_child"]] = "n_child"

    # income / scale
    inc = VP.get("income", {})
    if inc.get("weekly_disp_hh") in df.columns:
        rename_map[inc["weekly_disp_hh"]] = "disp_income_week"
    demo = VP.get("demo", {})
    if demo.get("eq_scale") in df.columns:
        rename_map[demo["eq_scale"]] = "eq_scale"

    # demographic codes → *_code
    code_targets = {
        "sex": "sex_code",
        "emp": "emp_code",
        "eth": "eth_code",
        "mar": "mar_code",
        "tenure": "tenure_code",
        "educ": "educ_code",
        "region": "region_code",
        "lone_parent": "lone_parent",
    }
    for k, outname in code_targets.items():
        col = demo.get(k)
        if col in df.columns:
            rename_map[col] = outname

    # apply rename
    df = df.rename(columns=rename_map)

    # numeric-ify obvious numerics (safe)
    numeric_cols = [
        "age","hh_size","n_adult","n_child","disp_income_week","eq_scale",
        "sex_code","emp_code","eth_code","mar_code","tenure_code","educ_code",
        "region_code","lone_parent"
    ]
    for c in numeric_cols:
        if c in df.columns:
            df[c] = pd.to_numeric(df[c], errors="coerce")

    # nice column order (whatever exists gets kept in this order)
    preferred_order = [
        "case","hh_size","n_adult","n_child","age",
        "sex_code","emp_code","eth_code","mar_code","tenure_code","educ_code",
        "region_code","lone_parent",
        "disp_income_week","eq_scale",
    ]
    cols = [c for c in preferred_order if c in df.columns] + \
           [c for c in df.columns if c not in preferred_order]
    return df[cols]

# use it
merged = standardise_columns(merged, VARIABLE_PLAN)

# ---- Build human-readable labels from .sav metadata and apply to merged ----
import pyreadstat
import pandas as pd

def load_label_lookup_from_sav(paths):
    """
    Load multiple .sav files and build a combined lookup:
    return dict with case-insensitive variable names -> value-label dicts
    """
    lookup = {}
    for p in paths:
        try:
            _, meta = pyreadstat.read_sav(p)
            for var, labels in meta.variable_value_labels.items():
                # Keep original and lower-case alias for robust lookup
                lookup[var] = labels
                lookup[var.lower()] = labels
        except Exception as e:
            print(f"[note] Could not read labels from {p}: {e}")
    return lookup

def _coerce_label_keys_both_int_and_float(label_dict):
    """
    SPSS labels often use float keys (e.g. 1.0). Build a mapping that
    accepts both integer and float codes.
    """
    out = {}
    for k, v in label_dict.items():
        out[k] = v
        try:
            # add int version if safe (1.0 -> 1)
            if float(k).is_integer():
                out[int(float(k))] = v
        except Exception:
            pass
    return out

def apply_demo_labels(merged, VARIABLE_PLAN, label_lookup, suffix="_cat"):
    """
    For each demo code in VARIABLE_PLAN, create a human-readable column
    next to the *_code column using the .sav label lookup.
    """
    # mapping of demo keys -> (final code col name in merged, suffix col name)
    code_targets = {
        "sex":       "sex_code",
        "emp":       "emp_code",
        "eth":       "eth_code",
        "mar":       "mar_code",
        "tenure":    "tenure_code",
        "educ":      "educ_code",
        "region":    "region_code",
        "lone_parent":"lone_parent",   # may already be 0/1 without labels
    }

    created = []
    for demo_key, code_col in code_targets.items():
        if code_col not in merged.columns:
            continue
        src_var = VARIABLE_PLAN["demo"].get(demo_key)  # e.g. "A004", "HighEd1"
        if not src_var:
            continue

        # Find label dict by original source variable name (case-insensitive)
        lab = (
            label_lookup.get(src_var)
            or label_lookup.get(src_var.lower())
        )
        if not lab:
            # nothing to map for this variable (fine: we just keep *_code)
            continue

        # Make mapping robust to int/float code representations
        lab_map = _coerce_label_keys_both_int_and_float(lab)

        # Build human-readable column
        out_col = code_col.replace("_code", suffix) if "_code" in code_col else f"{code_col}{suffix}"
        # Ensure numeric-ish codes can align with the label keys
        ser = pd.to_numeric(merged[code_col], errors="coerce")
        merged[out_col] = ser.map(lab_map)

        created.append((code_col, out_col, src_var))

    if created:
        print("Created label columns:")
        for code_col, out_col, src in created:
            print(f"  {code_col} -> {out_col}   [from {src}]")
    else:
        print("[note] No label columns created (no matching labels found).")

    return merged

# ---- Section 3: Equivalise income + quick stats + plots (Steps 1–3) ----
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from pathlib import Path

# Work on a reference to your merged table
df = merged.copy()

# 1) Equivalise disposable income (baseline)
# Prefer a standardised 'eq_scale' if you already renamed; else try raw 'OECDSc'; else fallback from n_adult/n_child
if "eq_scale" in df.columns:
    df["eq_hh_size"] = pd.to_numeric(df["eq_scale"], errors="coerce")
elif "OECDSc" in df.columns:
    df["eq_hh_size"] = pd.to_numeric(df["OECDSc"], errors="coerce")
else:
    a = pd.to_numeric(df.get("n_adult"), errors="coerce")
    c = pd.to_numeric(df.get("n_child"), errors="coerce")
    df["eq_hh_size"] = 1.0 + np.maximum((a - 1), 0) * 0.5 + (c.fillna(0) * 0.3)

# Income to numeric
df["disp_income_week"] = pd.to_numeric(df["disp_income_week"], errors="coerce")

# Equivalised income (baseline)
df["eq_pre"] = df["disp_income_week"] / df["eq_hh_size"]

# 2) Quick stats to guide winsorise/log decisions
def p_ratio(series, p_hi=0.99, p_mid=0.50):
    s = pd.to_numeric(series, errors="coerce")
    q_hi = s.quantile(p_hi)
    q_md = s.quantile(p_mid)
    return (q_hi / q_md) if (q_md and q_md != 0) else np.nan

stats = {
    "raw_median":      float(df["disp_income_week"].median(skipna=True)),
    "raw_skew":        float(df["disp_income_week"].skew(skipna=True)),
    "raw_P99/P50":     float(p_ratio(df["disp_income_week"], 0.99, 0.50)),
    "eq_median":       float(df["eq_pre"].median(skipna=True)),
    "eq_skew":         float(df["eq_pre"].skew(skipna=True)),
    "eq_P99/P50":      float(p_ratio(df["eq_pre"], 0.99, 0.50)),
    "n_missing_eq_pre": int(df["eq_pre"].isna().sum()),
}
print("=== Summary (use this to decide on winsorise/log) ===")
for k, v in stats.items():
    print(f"{k:>16}: {v}")

# 3) Plots: raw vs equivalised
def hist1(series, title, xlabel, bins=40):
    s = pd.to_numeric(series, errors="coerce").dropna()
    plt.figure(figsize=(7.2,4.6))
    sns.histplot(s, bins=bins, kde=True)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel); plt.ylabel("Count"); plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

hist1(df["disp_income_week"], "Raw disposable income (weekly)", "£ per week (household)")
hist1(df["eq_pre"],           "Equivalised income (weekly)",    "£ per week (equivalised)")

# Optional: save figures if your FIG_DIR exists in CONFIG
try:
    fig_dir = Path(CONFIG["FIG_DIR"]) / "section3"
    fig_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    # Re-plot and save
    for ser, ttl, fname in [

except Exception as e:
    print(f"[note] Skipped saving figures: {e}")

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats.mstats import winsorize

# --- Pick the right dataframe variable here ---
df = merged   # <-- if your df is called merged_df, change this line to: df = merged_df

# Quick sanity check
print("Has eq_income_week?", "eq_income_week" in df.columns)
print("Columns example:", list(df.columns)[:10])

# (Re)compute equivalised income if needed
if "eq_income_week" not in df.columns:
    if {"disp_income_week", "hh_size"}.issubset(df.columns):
        disp = pd.to_numeric(df["disp_income_week"], errors="coerce")
        eqsz = pd.to_numeric(df["hh_size"], errors="coerce")
        df["eq_income_week"] = disp / eqsz
        print("✅ Recomputed eq_income_week from disp_income_week / hh_size.")
    else:
        raise KeyError("Missing prerequisites to build eq_income_week: need 'disp_income_week' and 'hh_size'.")

# --- Winsorise at 1st/99th percentiles (both tails) ---
s = pd.to_numeric(df["eq_income_week"], errors="coerce")
w = winsorize(s.to_numpy(), limits=(0.01, 0.01))       # returns a masked array
w = np.asarray(w, dtype=float)                         # plain numpy array

df["eq_income_week_winz"] = pd.Series(w, index=df.index)

# --- Log transform (clip negatives to 0 to avoid log of <= 0) ---
df["log_eq_income"] = np.log1p(np.clip(df["eq_income_week_winz"], 0, None))

print("✅ Added columns: 'eq_income_week_winz', 'log_eq_income'")
print(df[["eq_income_week","eq_income_week_winz","log_eq_income"]].head())

def p_ratio(series, p_hi=0.99, p_mid=0.50):
    s = pd.to_numeric(series, errors="coerce").dropna()
    q_hi = s.quantile(p_hi)
    q_md = s.quantile(p_mid)
    return float(q_hi / q_md) if (q_md and q_md != 0) else np.nan

def stats_for(name, series):
    s = pd.to_numeric(series, errors="coerce").dropna()
    return {
        "count":     int(s.size),
        "missing":   int(series.isna().sum()),
        "min":       float(np.nanmin(s)) if s.size else np.nan,
        "p25":       float(np.nanpercentile(s, 25)) if s.size else np.nan,
        "p50":       float(np.nanmedian(s)) if s.size else np.nan,
        "p75":       float(np.nanpercentile(s, 75)) if s.size else np.nan,
        "p99":       float(np.nanpercentile(s, 99)) if s.size else np.nan,
        "max":       float(np.nanmax(s)) if s.size else np.nan,
        "skew":      float(s.skew()) if s.size else np.nan,
        "P99/P50":   p_ratio(series, 0.99, 0.50),
        "negatives": int((s < 0).sum()) if s.size else 0,
        "zeros":     int((s == 0).sum()) if s.size else 0,
    }

              "tenure_code","region_code","educ_code","lone_parent"]

# Numeric -> median
for c in NUM_IMPUTE:
    mlc = f"{c}_ml"
    df[mlc] = pd.to_numeric(df[c], errors="coerce")
    med = df[mlc].median()
    df[mlc] = df[mlc].fillna(med)
    df[f"{c}_was_missing"] = df[c].isna().astype(int)

# Categorical -> mode (most frequent code)
for c in CAT_IMPUTE:
    mlc = f"{c}_ml"
    df[mlc] = pd.to_numeric(df[c], errors="coerce")
    mode_val = df[mlc].mode(dropna=True)

    df[f"{c}_was_missing"] = df[mlc].isna().astype(int)

# Summary function
def describe_demographics(df, cols):
    summaries = {}
    for col in cols:
        if df[col].dtype == "object" or df[col].dtype.name == "category":
            counts = df[col].value_counts(dropna=False)
            perc = df[col].value_counts(normalize=True, dropna=False) * 100
            summary = pd.DataFrame({"count": counts, "percent": perc.round(1)})
        else:
            summary = df[col].describe(percentiles=[.25, .5, .75]).to_frame(name=col)
        summaries[col] = summary
    return summaries

# Run

# Print each nicely

    print(f"\n--- {col} ---")

4. UBI Microsimulation¶

Goal: apply policy scenarios to the baseline data and compute post-transfer incomes.

What we do

  • Define scenarios (from CONFIG)
    • Examples: Full UBI (flat rate per adult/child per week), Automation Dividend, GMI (means-tested top-up).
    • Parameters stored in CONFIG["SCENARIOS"] (rates, child rates if used, eligibility toggles).
  • Eligibility & unit of assessment
    • Compute household entitlement from composition (adults/children) and scenario rules.
    • Optionally include take-up rates or caps (document if not used).
  • Integrate with baseline
    • post_income = baseline_disposable_income + transfers − clawbacks/taxes (if modelled).
    • Guarantee non-negative disposable income.
  • Sanity checks
    • Totals and per-capita transfer summaries, min/median/max shifts.
    • No missing values introduced.

# Helpers — Gini & poverty line
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

def gini(x: pd.Series) -> float:
    """Gini on non-negative values (ignores NaNs). Returns between 0 and 1."""
    v = x.dropna().astype(float).values
    if v.size == 0:
        return np.nan
    v = np.sort(np.clip(v, 0, None))
    s = v.sum()
    if s == 0:
        return 0.0
    n = v.size
    cum = np.cumsum(v)
    return (n + 1 - 2 * (cum.sum() / s)) / n

def poverty_line_eq60(eq_income: pd.Series) -> float:
    med = np.nanmedian(eq_income)
    return 0.6 * med

# Core simulator
def simulate_ubi(
    df: pd.DataFrame,
    per_adult: float = 0.0,
    per_child: float | None = None,
    per_person: float | None = None,
    clawback_rate: float = 0.0,           # e.g. 0.2 means 20% clawback
    clawback_exemption: float = np.inf,   # income above which clawback applies
    name: str = "UBI"
) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """
    Build a counterfactual disposable & equivalised income under a UBI scheme.
    - If per_person is set, it overrides per_adult/per_child and pays per hh_size.
    - Clawback is linear: clawback_rate * max(disp - exemption, 0).
    """
    req = ["disp_income_week", "eq_scale", "hh_size", "n_adult", "n_child"]
    missing = [c for c in req if c not in df.columns]
    if missing:
        raise KeyError(f"simulate_ubi() missing columns: {missing}")

    out = df.copy()

    # Grant calculation
    if per_person is not None:
        grant = per_person * out["hh_size"]
    else:
        if per_child is None:
            per_child = per_adult  # if not specified, same as adult
        grant = per_adult * out["n_adult"] + per_child * out["n_child"]

    # Simple linear clawback on income above an exemption
    base = out["disp_income_week"]
    clawback_base = np.clip(base - clawback_exemption, a_min=0, a_max=None)
    clawback = clawback_rate * clawback_base

    # New incomes
    out[f"disp_{name}"] = base + grant - clawback
    out[f"eq_{name}"]   = out[f"disp_{name}"] / out["eq_scale"]

    # Uplifts
    out[f"uplift_abs_{name}"] = out[f"disp_{name}"] - base
    out[f"uplift_pct_{name}"] = np.where(
        base != 0, out[f"uplift_abs_{name}"] / np.abs(base), np.nan
    )

    return out

    Compare baseline vs simulated scenario on:
    - Median equivalised income
    - Gini coefficient
    - Poverty rate (<60% baseline median)
    """
    if baseline_eq_col not in df_before.columns:
        raise KeyError(f"Need '{baseline_eq_col}' in the baseline df.")

    eq_b = df_before[baseline_eq_col]      # <-- use winsorised baseline
    if f"eq_{name}" not in df_after.columns:
        raise KeyError(f"Need 'eq_{name}' in the simulated df.")
    eq_a = df_after[f"eq_{name}"]

    # Poverty threshold from *baseline* (60% of median equivalised income)
    pov_line = poverty_line_eq60(eq_b)


    metrics = []

    def row(title, s):
        return dict(
            metric=title,
            before=(
                np.nanmedian(eq_b) if title == "Median equivalised income"
                else gini(eq_b) if title == "Gini (equivalised)"
                else (eq_b < pov_line).mean() if title.startswith("Poverty")
                else np.nan
            ),
            after=(
                np.nanmedian(eq_a) if title == "Median equivalised income"
                else gini(eq_a) if title == "Gini (equivalised)"
                else (eq_a < pov_line).mean() if title.startswith("Poverty")
                else np.nan
            )
        )

    metrics.append(row("Median equivalised income", None))
    metrics.append(row("Gini (equivalised)", None))
    metrics.append(row("Poverty rate (<60% baseline median)", None))

    tbl = pd.DataFrame(metrics)
    tbl["change"] = tbl["after"] - tbl["before"]

    print(f"\n=== Headline metrics: {name} ===")
    display(tbl.style.format({
        "before": "{:.2f}",
        "after": "{:.2f}",
        "change": "{:+.2f}"
    }))

    return tbl

def poverty_rates_both(df_before, df_after, name, base_col="eq_income_week_winz"):
    """
    Returns a 1-row DataFrame with both poverty rates:
      - anchored:   line = 60% of median(baseline eq income)
      - relative:   line = 60% of median(after-policy eq income)
    """
    if base_col not in df_before.columns:
        raise KeyError(f"Need '{base_col}' in df_before.")
    after_col = f"eq_{name}"
    if after_col not in df_after.columns:
        raise KeyError(f"Need '{after_col}' in df_after.")

    eq_b = pd.to_numeric(df_before[base_col], errors="coerce")
    eq_a = pd.to_numeric(df_after[after_col], errors="coerce")

    # Anchored poverty line (baseline)
    pov_line_anch = 0.6 * np.nanmedian(eq_b)
    # Relative poverty line (post-policy)
    pov_line_rel  = 0.6 * np.nanmedian(eq_a)

    anchored = np.nanmean(eq_a < pov_line_anch) * 100.0
    relative = np.nanmean(eq_a < pov_line_rel) * 100.0

    return pd.DataFrame([{
        "scenario": name,
        "poverty_rate_anchored_%": anchored,
        "poverty_rate_relative_%": relative,
        "baseline_median_eq": np.nanmedian(eq_b),
        "after_median_eq":    np.nanmedian(eq_a)
    }])

# Who benefits most?” (group uplift)
# This answers your RQ1. It ranks groups by median % uplift (and shows mean too).
def group_uplift_table(
    df_sim: pd.DataFrame,
    name: str,
    group_cols = ("sex_cat","emp_cat","educ_cat","region_cat","mar_cat","tenure_cat","lone_parent_cat")
):
    col = f"uplift_pct_{name}"
    if col not in df_sim.columns:
        raise KeyError(f"Need '{col}' in df_sim. Run simulate_ubi() first.")

    # Build one big table per grouping variable
    outputs = {}
    for g in group_cols:
        if g not in df_sim.columns:
            continue
        tmp = (df_sim
               .groupby(g, dropna=False)[col]
               .agg(median_uplift="median", mean_uplift="mean", count="size")
               .sort_values("median_uplift", ascending=False))
        outputs[g] = tmp
        print(f"\n=== Uplift by {g} ({name}) ===")
        display(tmp.style.format({"median_uplift":"{:+.2%}", "mean_uplift":"{:+.2%}"}))
    return outputs

FULL_UBI_PW_ADULT      = CONFIG["SCENARIOS_MONTHLY"]["Full_UBI"] * MONTH_TO_WEEK
AUTO_DIVIDEND_PW_ADULT = CONFIG["SCENARIOS_MONTHLY"]["Automation_Dividend"] * MONTH_TO_WEEK

# Baseline
baseline = merged  # must include: disp_income_week, eq_income_week, eq_scale, n_adult, n_child, hh_size

# === Scenario 1: Full UBI (£500/month/adult ≈ £115/week/adult) ===
sim_fullubi = simulate_ubi(
    baseline,
    per_adult=FULL_UBI_PW_ADULT,
    clawback_rate=0.0,
    name="FullUBI"
)

# === Scenario 2: Automation Dividend (£200/month/adult ≈ £46/week/adult) ===
sim_auto = simulate_ubi(
    baseline,
    per_adult=AUTO_DIVIDEND_PW_ADULT,
    clawback_rate=0.0,
    name="AutomationDividend"
)

# === Scenario 3: GMI — top up to 60% of median equivalised income (equivalised floor) ===
poverty_threshold_eq = poverty_line_eq60(baseline[EQ_BASE_COL])
hh_threshold = poverty_threshold_eq * baseline["eq_scale"]

sim_gmi = baseline.copy()
sim_gmi["disp_GMI"] = np.where(
    baseline["disp_income_week"] < hh_threshold,
    hh_threshold,
    baseline["disp_income_week"]
)
sim_gmi["eq_GMI"] = sim_gmi["disp_GMI"] / sim_gmi["eq_scale"]


# Add uplift columns so group_uplift_table() can work
base = baseline["disp_income_week"]
sim_gmi["uplift_abs_GMI"] = sim_gmi["disp_GMI"] - base
sim_gmi["uplift_pct_GMI"] = np.where(
    base != 0, sim_gmi["uplift_abs_GMI"] / np.abs(base), np.nan
)


# === Who benefits most? (group uplift) ===
_ = group_uplift_table(sim_fullubi, "FullUBI")
_ = group_uplift_table(sim_auto, "AutomationDividend")
_ = group_uplift_table(sim_gmi, "GMI")

def save_group_uplifts(outs, name):
    for gcol, df_g in outs.items():
        save_table(df_g.reset_index(), f"simulation/group_uplift_{gcol}_{name}")

outs_full = group_uplift_table(sim_fullubi, "FullUBI")
save_group_uplifts(outs_full, "FullUBI")

outs_auto = group_uplift_table(sim_auto, "AutomationDividend")
save_group_uplifts(outs_auto, "AutomationDividend")

outs_gmi = group_uplift_table(sim_gmi, "GMI")
save_group_uplifts(outs_gmi, "GMI")

tbl_gmi = compare_headlines(baseline, sim_gmi,     "GMI",               baseline_eq_col=EQ_BASE_COL)


# Merge results side by side

)

    on="metric"
)

# Save combined table

pov_gmi  = poverty_rates_both(baseline, sim_gmi,     "GMI", base_col=EQ_BASE_COL)

display(pov_both)

# Lorenz curve (before/after) + Gini change bar
def lorenz_points(x):
    v = np.sort(pd.to_numeric(x, errors="coerce").dropna().clip(lower=0))
    if v.size == 0: return np.array([0,1]), np.array([0,1])
    cum = np.cumsum(v); cum = cum / cum[-1]
    p = np.arange(1, v.size+1) / v.size
    return np.insert(p,0,0), np.insert(cum,0,0)

def plot_lorenz(before, after, label_after):
    p_b, l_b = lorenz_points(baseline[EQ_BASE_COL])
    p_a, l_a = lorenz_points(after[f"eq_{label_after}"])
    plt.figure(figsize=(5,4))
    plt.plot(p_b, l_b, label="Baseline")
    plt.plot(p_a, l_a, label=label_after)
    plt.plot([0,1],[0,1], linestyle="--", alpha=.6)
    plt.xlabel("Cumulative population"); plt.ylabel("Cumulative income share")
    plt.title(f"Lorenz curve — {label_after}"); plt.legend()
    save_fig(f"simulation/lorenz_{label_after}")


# Example:
plot_lorenz(baseline, sim_fullubi, "FullUBI")
plot_lorenz(baseline, sim_auto, "AutomationDividend")

# Decile uplift analysis (table + bar)
def add_deciles(df, col=EQ_BASE_COL, k=10):
    q = pd.qcut(df[col], q=k, labels=[f"D{d}" for d in range(1,k+1)])
    return q

# Apply to baseline to define deciles once
baseline = baseline.copy()
baseline["decile"] = add_deciles(baseline, EQ_BASE_COL)

def uplift_by_decile(df_sim, name):
    col = f"uplift_pct_{name}"
    tbl = (pd.concat([baseline["decile"], df_sim[col]], axis=1)
             .groupby("decile", dropna=False)
             .agg(median_uplift=("uplift_pct_"+name,"median"),
                  mean_uplift=("uplift_pct_"+name,"mean"),
                  n=("uplift_pct_"+name,"size"))
             .reset_index())
    display(tbl); save_table(tbl, f"simulation/uplift_by_decile_{name}")
    # bar
    ax = tbl.plot(x="decile", y="median_uplift", kind="bar", figsize=(6,4), legend=False)
    plt.ylabel("Median % uplift"); plt.title(f"Uplift by income decile — {name}")
    save_fig(f"simulation/uplift_by_decile_{name}"); plt.show()
    return tbl

uplift_by_decile(sim_fullubi, "FullUBI")
uplift_by_decile(sim_auto, "AutomationDividend")
uplift_by_decile(sim_gmi, "GMI")

5. Machine Learning¶

Goal: Predict financial vulnerability (poverty risk) from pre-intervention demographic and economic features.

  • Target definition
    Poverty status defined as is_poor = 1[equivalised_income < 0.6 * median].
    Used log-transformed, winsorised income (log_eq_income_week_winz) to stabilise distribution.

  • Train/test split (no leakage)
    Split data into train/test, then applied preprocessing inside a scikit-learn Pipeline.

  • Preprocessing

    • Numeric: median imputation + scaling
    • Categorical: imputation as “Unknown” + one-hot encoding

  • Models

    • Logistic Regression (baseline, interpretable)
    • Random Forest (non-linear benchmark)
    • (Optional) Gradient Boosting

  • Evaluation

    • Metrics: Accuracy, ROC-AUC, Confusion Matrix
    • Feature importance (tree-based) and coefficients (logistic regression) to interpret predictors of poverty risk

# Section 6 – ML on UBI Uplift
# (ML-ready dataset, no income features) + Interpretability


ROOT = Path("/content/drive/MyDrive/UBI_Project")
sec3 = ROOT / "data" / "tables" / "section3"
full = sec3 / "ml_ready.csv"

# Load FULL dataset for modelling
df_ml = pd.read_csv(full)
print("ML dataset shape:", df_ml.shape)      # should be ~ (5133, ...)

# Make the rest of the block use the full data
df = df_ml.copy()

# Clean NA check on the *right* object
na = df.isnull().sum()
print("Cols with NAs > 0:\n", na[na > 0])
assert na.sum() == 0, "There are missing values in ml_ready.csv"

# 1) Identify baseline & construct post-UBI income
BASE = "eq_income_week_winz_ml"
if BASE not in df.columns:
    raise KeyError(f"Expected baseline '{BASE}' not found. Available columns: {df.columns.tolist()}")

# Try to find a weekly grant column to build POST = BASE + GRANT
grant_candidates = [
    "ubi_grant_week_ml", "ubi_grant_week", "ubi_amount_week_ml", "ubi_amount_week",
    "grant_week_ml", "grant_week"
]
GRANT_COL = next((c for c in grant_candidates if c in df.columns), None)

if GRANT_COL is not None:
    POST = "post_eq_income_week_calc"
    df[POST] = df[BASE] + df[GRANT_COL]
    print(f"Constructed POST from grant column: {POST} = {BASE} + {GRANT_COL}")
else:
    # Fallback: set a constant weekly grant (EDIT this value to your policy)
    GRANT_WEEK = 80.0  # e.g., £80/week per person; change to your policy
    POST = "post_eq_income_week_calc"
    df[POST] = df[BASE] + GRANT_WEEK
    print(f"Constructed POST with constant grant: {POST} = {BASE} + {GRANT_WEEK}")

#  2) Poverty line from baseline median (60%) and targets
MED_EQ = np.nanmedian(df[BASE].to_numpy())
POV_LINE = 0.60 * MED_EQ
df["is_poor_pre"]  = (df[BASE] < POV_LINE).astype(int)
df["is_poor_post"] = (df[POST] < POV_LINE).astype(int)
df["uplift_cross"] = ((df["is_poor_pre"] == 1) & (df["is_poor_post"] == 0)).astype(int)

# Optional descriptive targets (not used directly in classifiers)
df["uplift_abs"] = df[POST] - df[BASE]
df["uplift_rel"] = np.where(df[BASE] > 0, df["uplift_abs"] / df[BASE], np.nan)

print(f"Baseline median(eq) = {MED_EQ:.2f}, poverty line (60%) = {POV_LINE:.2f}")
print("Share crossing out of poverty:", df["uplift_cross"].mean().round(3))

#  3) Features: DEMOGRAPHICS ONLY (exclude income-derived)
exclude_exact = {
    BASE, POST, "log_eq_income_ml", "eq_income_week_winz_ml",
    "is_poor_pre", "is_poor_post", "uplift_cross", "uplift_abs", "uplift_rel"
}
exclude_if_contains = ("income", "eq_")

cand_cols = [c for c in df.columns
             if c not in exclude_exact and not any(k in c for k in exclude_if_contains)]

# Treat code variables and *_was_missing as categorical (even if stored as integers)
likely_cat = {c for c in cand_cols
              if c.endswith("_code_ml") or c.endswith("_was_missing") or c == "lone_parent_ml"}

# Age is the only true numeric in your list
num_cols = [c for c in cand_cols if c not in likely_cat]       # e.g., ['age_ml']
cat_cols = [c for c in cand_cols if c in likely_cat]

print("Num features:", num_cols)
print("Cat features:", cat_cols)


# 4) Train/test split
y = df["uplift_cross"]
X = df[num_cols + cat_cols].copy()

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

#  5) Preprocess (sklearn >=1.2) — robust to empty cat_cols
numeric_tf = Pipeline(steps=[
    ("scaler", StandardScaler(with_mean=False))
])

transformers = [("num", numeric_tf, num_cols)]

if len(cat_cols) > 0:
    categorical_tf = Pipeline(steps=[
        ("onehot", OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore", sparse_output=True))
    ])
    transformers.append(("cat", categorical_tf, cat_cols))

preprocess = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=transformers,
    remainder="drop",
    sparse_threshold=1.0
)


#  6) Models
models = {
    "logreg_no_income": LogisticRegression(
        solver="saga", max_iter=3000, class_weight="balanced"
    ),
    "rf_no_income": RandomForestClassifier(
        n_estimators=500, random_state=42, class_weight="balanced_subsample"
    ),
}

# Helpers
def fitted_feature_names(fitted_pipe):
    names = list(num_cols)
    # Only add OHE names if we actually had categorical columns
    if len(cat_cols) > 0:
        ohe = (fitted_pipe.named_steps["prep"]
               .named_transformers_["cat"]
               .named_steps["onehot"])
        names += ohe.get_feature_names_out(cat_cols).tolist()
    return np.array(names)

# Output dirs
FIG_DIR = ROOT / "figures" / "section6"
TABLE_DIR = ROOT / "data" / "tables" / "section6"
FIG_DIR.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
TABLE_DIR.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

rows = []
for name, estimator in models.items():
    pipe = Pipeline(steps=[("prep", preprocess), ("clf", estimator)])
    pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Predict
    y_pred = pipe.predict(X_test)
    if hasattr(pipe[-1], "predict_proba"):
        y_proba = pipe.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
    else:
        s = pipe.decision_function(X_test)
        s = (s - s.min()) / (s.max() - s.min() + 1e-12)
        y_proba = s

    # Metrics
    acc  = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    prec = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, zero_division=0)
    rec  = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, zero_division=0)
    f1   = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, zero_division=0)
    auc  = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba)
    rows.append([name, "no_income", acc, prec, rec, f1, auc])

    # Figures: Confusion Matrix
    fig_cm, ax_cm = plt.subplots(figsize=(4.8, 4.6))
    ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_test, y_pred, ax=ax_cm)
    ax_cm.set_title(f"Confusion Matrix — {name}")
    fig_cm.tight_layout()
    fig_cm.savefig(FIG_DIR / f"confusion_{name}.png", dpi=160)
    plt.show()

    # Figures: ROC
    fig_roc, ax_roc = plt.subplots(figsize=(5.6, 4.6))
    RocCurveDisplay.from_predictions(y_test, y_proba, ax=ax_roc, name=name)
    ax_roc.set_title(f"ROC — {name}  (AUC={auc:.3f})")
    fig_roc.tight_layout()
    fig_roc.savefig(FIG_DIR / f"roc_{name}.png", dpi=160)
    plt.show()

    # Interpretability
    feats = fitted_feature_names(pipe)

    if name.startswith("logreg"):
        coefs = pipe.named_steps["clf"].coef_[0]
        odds = np.exp(coefs)
        coef_df = pd.DataFrame({"feature": feats, "coef": coefs, "odds_ratio": odds}) \
                    .sort_values("odds_ratio", ascending=False)
        display(coef_df.head(20))
        coef_df.to_csv(TABLE_DIR / f"coef_{name}.csv", index=False)

        # Bar: top 15 by |coef|
        topN = coef_df.reindex(coef_df["coef"].abs().sort_values(ascending=False).index)[:15]
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7.5, 6))
        ax.barh(topN["feature"], topN["coef"])
        ax.set_title(f"Logistic Coefficients (top |coef|) — {name}")
        ax.invert_yaxis()
        fig.tight_layout()
        fig.savefig(FIG_DIR / f"coefbar_{name}.png", dpi=160)
        plt.show()

    if name.startswith("rf"):
        importances = pipe.named_steps["clf"].feature_importances_
        imp_df = pd.DataFrame({"feature": feats, "importance": importances}) \
                    .sort_values("importance", ascending=False)
        display(imp_df.head(20))
        imp_df.to_csv(TABLE_DIR / f"featimp_{name}.csv", index=False)

        # Bar: top 15 importances
        topI = imp_df.head(15).iloc[::-1]
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7.5, 6))
        ax.barh(topI["feature"], topI["importance"])
        ax.set_title(f"Feature Importance (top 15) — {name}")
        fig.tight_layout()
        fig.savefig(FIG_DIR / f"featimpbar_{name}.png", dpi=160)
        plt.show()

# 7) Metrics table
results = pd.DataFrame(rows, columns=["model","features","accuracy","precision","recall","f1","roc_auc"])
display(results.sort_values(["features","model"]).reset_index(drop=True))
results.to_csv(TABLE_DIR / "model_metrics_uplift.csv", index=False)

print("Saved:")
print(f"- metrics -> {TABLE_DIR / 'model_metrics_uplift.csv'}")
print(f"- figures (confusion_*, roc_*, coefbar_*, featimpbar_*) -> {FIG_DIR}")
print(f"- coefficients / importances CSVs -> {TABLE_DIR}")

# 1) Define the training feature set used now (no income var if that’s your spec)
X_train_no_income = X_train.drop(columns=['eq_income_week'], errors='ignore')
X_test_no_income  = X_test.drop(columns=['eq_income_week'], errors='ignore')

# 2) Save the exact column order for reuse at predict-time
feature_cols_no_income = X_train_no_income.columns.tolist()

# 3) Fit models using DATAFRAMES (keeps feature names)
logreg_no_income = LogisticRegression(solver="saga", max_iter=3000, class_weight="balanced")
rf_no_income     = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=500, random_state=42, class_weight="balanced_subsample")

logreg_no_income.fit(X_train_no_income, y_train)
rf_no_income.fit(X_train_no_income, y_train)

# 4) Predict (with aligned columns) and plot PR (example)
from sklearn.metrics import PrecisionRecallDisplay, average_precision_score

def aligned(df, cols):
    return df.reindex(columns=cols, fill_value=0)  # keeps order, adds any missing dummies as 0

Xte = aligned(X_test_no_income, feature_cols_no_income)

y_proba_log = logreg_no_income.predict_proba(Xte)[:, 1]
ap_log = average_precision_score(y_test, y_proba_log)
PrecisionRecallDisplay.from_predictions(y_test, y_proba_log, name=f"LogReg (AP={ap_log:.3f})")
plt.title("Precision–Recall Curve — Logistic Regression")
plt.savefig('/content/drive/MyDrive/prcurve_logreg.png', dpi=300)
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
